						               													<description>Bet Your Word is a poker-like word game where you try to make the best-scoring words.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Using letters in your hand and the central one showing, form your best word and bet to see if it is better than that of your opponent(s).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;SETUP: &amp;#10;1. Shuffle the cards and place into a draw pile.&amp;#10;2. Give each player an equal number of coins.&amp;#10;3. Give each player five cards to hold in secret.&amp;#10;&amp;emsp;&amp;#10;GAME PLAY: &amp;#10;On each turn:&amp;#10;&amp;bull; A player flips over the next card from the draw pile&amp;#10;&amp;bull; Each player antes one &amp;ldquo;cent&amp;rdquo;&amp;#10;&amp;bull; Each player attempts to visualize a word using a combination of the central card any number of letters in their hand&amp;#10;&amp;bull; Any player can then bet a coin&amp;#10;&amp;bull; All players who wish to bet their word, must match the bet and can raise their bet as well&amp;#10;&amp;bull; When betting stops, the players reveal their words&amp;#10;&amp;bull; The player with the highest point value gathers all the letters played, all the coins and the central card&amp;#10;&amp;bull; Players can then replace up to five cards from the draw pile&amp;#10;&amp;bull; Players must maintain exactly five cards in their hands&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Play continues with the next player on the left.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game ends when no more cards can be drawn. At this point players add up their coin values and letter values to determine the winner. If there is a tie, the youngest player wins.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Two additional modes are possible.&amp;#10;Solo mode and &amp;quot;Multiple Choice&amp;quot; betting mode.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game comes with  &amp;#10;&amp;bull; 90 A-Z letter and bigram fragment cards &amp;#10;&amp;bull; 50 coins in various cent denominations&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game has two sizes&amp;quot;&amp;#10;2 inch cards in a 2x2x2 box or&amp;#10;full sized deck of 104 cards.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;-description from publisher&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
